    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my civil eng exam and im a bit confused. if concrete is already really strong, why do we actually need to put steel rebar inside it for foundations? like what is the actual relationship between the compressive strength of the concrete and the tensile strength of the steel?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Concrete excels in handling compressive forces, which is why it's great for supporting weight. However, concrete is very weak when stretched or bent—that's its low tensile strength. Steel rebar is incorporated specifically because it has very high tensile strength, allowing it to absorb those pulling forces that concrete cannot handle alone. Essentially, the concrete takes the squeezing load, while the steel takes the stretching load, creating a composite material that is much stronger overall.",
      "source": "target",
