    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so basically they work together as a team. but what happens if there's a crack or something goes wrong inside the slab? like, does the steel just keep it together or is there any way for the internal stresses to actually damage the concrete from the inside out?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When cracks form, the steel rebar is crucial because it restrains those cracks from widening significantly under tension. While the steel holds the pieces together, if the forces exceed the capacity of the steel, the cracks will still propagate and can expose the concrete to environmental damage like rust. Rusting steel can expand and exert tremendous internal pressure, which can then cause the surrounding concrete to spall or break apart.",
      "source": "target",
